 -->
                <p>Find the cubed value of a number
                    <em>n</em>. Enter positive or negative whole numbers, d=
ecimal numbers or scientific E notation.</p>
                <h2>What is a Cubed Number?</h2>
                <p>Any number <em>n</em> with an exponent of 3 is written a=
s
                    <em>n=C2=B3</em>. You pronounce it as "<em>n</em> cubed=
," or "<em>n</em> to the third power." To get the cube of a number multiply=
 it by itself 3 times.
                </p>
                <p>Therefore the cube formula is <em>n=C2=B3 =3D n =C3=97 n=
 =C3=97 n</em>.</p>
                <h2>What is a Perfect Cube?</h2>
                <p>A perfect cube results when you cube an integer, or a wh=
ole number without decimals or fractions. For example, 3 cubed is written a=
s 3=C2=B3 and 3=C2=B3 =3D 3 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 3 =3D 27.</p>
                <p>Since 3 is an integer, 27 is a perfect cube.</p>
                <p>Imagine a block of smaller cubes 3 high, 3 wide, and 3 d=
eep resembling a Rubik's Cube puzzle. Basically it's 3 sets of 9 blocks arr=
anged in a 3 x 3 pattern. Since 3 x 3 is 9 which is also 3 squared or 3<sup=
>2</sup>, you simply need to multiply by 3 again to get 3 cubed, 3<sup>3</s=
up> =3D 27.
                </p>
                <p>It might help to picture any cubed number as a set of bl=
ocks. 10<sup>3</sup>, or 10 cubed for example, would be a set of blocks 10 =
high, 10 wide and 10 deep. One face of the cube would have a set of 10<sup>=
2</sup> or 10 x 10 =3D 100 blocks. And 10 sets of those 100 blocks would be=
 10 x 100 =3D 1000 blocks.
                </p>
                <p class=3D"alignCenter">10 =C3=97 10 =C3=97 10 =3D 10 =C3=
=97 10<sup>2</sup> =3D 10 =C3=97 100 =3D 10<sup>3</sup> =3D 1000
                </p>
                <p>The image below is a large cube of 10=C2=B3 =3D 1000 sma=
ller cubes. Notice that each layer is 10 x 10 =3D 100 cubes.</p>
                <div align=3D"center">
                    <img src=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/images/algeb=
ra/cube-10x10x10.png" alt=3D"large cube made up of 10 cubed =3D 1000 cubes"=
 max=3D"" width=3D"300">
                </div>
                <h3>Numbers 0 through 10 cubed and the resulting perfect cu=
bes </h3>
                <ul>
                    <li>0 cubed is 0=C2=B3 =3D 0 =C3=97 0 =C3=97 0 =3D 0</l=
i>
                    <li>1 cubed is 1=C2=B3 =3D 1 =C3=97 1 =C3=97 1 =3D 1</l=
i>
                    <li>2 cubed is 2=C2=B3 =3D 2 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 2 =3D 8</l=
i>
                    <li>3 cubed is 3=C2=B3 =3D 3 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 3 =3D 27</=
li>
                    <li>4 cubed is 4=C2=B3 =3D 4 =C3=97 4 =C3=97 4 =3D 64</=
li>
                    <li>5 cubed is 5=C2=B3 =3D 5 =C3=97 5 =C3=97 5 =3D 125<=
/li>
                    <li>6 cubed is 6=C2=B3 =3D 6 =C3=97 6 =C3=97 6 =3D 216<=
/li>
                    <li>7 cubed is 7=C2=B3 =3D 7 =C3=97 7 =C3=97 7 =3D 343<=
/li>
                    <li>8 cubed is 8=C2=B3 =3D 8 =C3=97 8 =C3=97 8 =3D 512<=
/li>
                    <li>9 cubed is 9=C2=B3 =3D 9 =C3=97 9 =C3=97 9 =3D 729<=
/li>
                    <li>10 cubed is 10=C2=B3 =3D 10 =C3=97 10 =C3=97 10 =3D=
 1000</li>
                </ul>
                <p>See our
                    <a href=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/calculators/a=
lgebra/cubed-perfect-cubes.php">List of the First 100 Perfect Cubes</a>.
                </p>
                <h2>Cubing Negative Numbers</h2>
                <p>When you cube a negative number the result will always b=
e a negative number. But it is important to understand how using parenthese=
s affects the intepretation of the operation.</p>
                <p>Putting a negative sign before the number or outside of =
parentheses means "take the negative of the number, cubed" as in</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>-2=C2=B3 means -(2 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 2) =3D -8</li>
                    <li>-(2)=C2=B3 means -(2 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 2) =3D -8</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Putting a negative sign inside the parentheses means "cu=
be the negative number," as in</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>(-2)=C2=B3 means (-2 =C3=97 -2 =C3=97 -2) =3D -8</l=
i>
                </ul>
                <p>You can see you'll always get a negative result with an =
odd exponent and a negative sign, whether it's inside or outside of parenth=
eses. But when you have an even exponent the result depends on the interpre=
tation of the negative sign and the presence of parentheses.</p>
                <p>It may be helpful to use parentheses to clearly indicate=
 which exponent calculation you intend. For example with even exponents and=
 a negative sign the parentheses affect the result. </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>-4=C2=B2 means -(4 =C3=97 4) =3D -16</li>
                    <li>-(4)=C2=B2 means -(4 =C3=97 4) =3D -16</li>
                    <li>(-4)=C2=B2 means (-4 =C3=97 -4) =3D 16</li>
                </ul>
                <p>You can see that the
                    <a href=3D"https://www.calculatorsoup.com/calculators/a=
lgebra/square-calculator.php?number=3D-4&amp;action=3Dsolve" target=3D"_bla=
nk">Square Calculator</a> uses this strict interpretation. Without parenthe=
ses -4=C2=B2 means "the negative of 4=C2=B2" which is -16.
                </p>
                <h3>Additional Reading</h3>
                <p>Wikipedia "Cube (algebra)" at
                    <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cube_(algebra)=
">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cube_(algebra)</a>
                </p>
